Lesson 1 = Long Vs Short Czech Vowels ==================================================================================================================================================================================================
Free Lesson/Quiz (pdf download) : 
https://czechwithkaterina.cz/product/lesson-1/
Short Vowels = A a, E e , I i / Y y , O o , U u (same vowels as English)
Long Vowels = √Å √°	 , √â √©	, √ç √≠	/ √ù √Ω , √ì √≥	, √ö √∫	 , ≈Æ ≈Ø = Pronounced same as short vowels, but longer, twice as long - I / Y pronounced the same
The long sign above a vowel shows the 'length' of the vowel, not the 'stress' of the vowel
The length of a vowel can cahnge the meaning of the word (byt = appartment / b√Ωt = to be) 
Diphtongs = 2 vowels next to each other = ou / au / eu 
Vowels are not merged, each vowel is pronounced clearly with their own sound

